lic <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’. This is one of the most common Old Irish personal names. It is derived from <i>Lugh</i> ‘brightness’, which was the name of a Celtic god."],"variants":[{"name":"Laws","meanings":["English: variant of   Law   (pet form of   Lawrence  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish or Irish   McLeish  . Compare   McLaws  ."]},{"name":"Lewison","meanings":["Welsh and English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Lewis   (in Wales this was taken as equivalent to the Welsh personal name   Llewelyn  ). In North America, this surname has reportedly absorbed in some cases the Greek patronymic   Iliopoulos  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name <i>Lewi</i>, Polish-influenced form of   Levy  ."]},{"name":"McGlew","meanings":["Irish: most probably from <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’, a Gaelic personal name (referencing the god Lugh), sometimes Anglicized as   Lewis  . However, both Woulfe and MacLysaght consider <i>McGlew</i> to be a shortened form of <b>Mac Dhuinnshléibhe</b> (see   McAleavey   and   Dunleavy  )."]},{"name":"Lowis","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewis   1."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lwerdd Verch Lewys had at least 1 son with Madoc ap Hywel Fychan."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1252–1278":"1252–1278","–Female":"Surnud","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","about 1252":"umbes 1252","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1252–1278":"1252–1278","–Female":"Kuollut","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","about 1252":"noin 1252","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1252–1278":"1252–1278","–Female":"Décédée","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","about 1252":"environ 1252","Llanwinio, Carmar